<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993"><gtr:id>68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Manchester</gtr:name><gtr:department>Social Sciences</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Oxford Road</gtr:line1><gtr:city>Manchester</gtr:city><gtr:postCode>M13 9PL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>North West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993"><gtr:id>68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Manchester</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Oxford Road</gtr:line1><gtr:city>Manchester</gtr:city><gtr:postCode>M13 9PL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>North West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C8DB6585-402D-45C8-8760-6194CCD64FCF"><gtr:id>C8DB6585-402D-45C8-8760-6194CCD64FCF</gtr:id><gtr:name>Department for Culture Media and Sport</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>2-4 Cockspur Street</gtr:line1><gtr:postCode>SW1Y 5DH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_FUNDER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/5B2EEAE2-76A8-4DDB-85F7-1F0A40D3F3AC"><gtr:id>5B2EEAE2-76A8-4DDB-85F7-1F0A40D3F3AC</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Andrew</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Graham</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Miles</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-5547-249X</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0139"><gtr:id>FBE54B68-F50D-41C5-BFA7-BD2FF5916C9B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding the Relationship Between Taste &amp;amp; Value in Culture &amp;amp; Sport</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0139</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>What does it mean to 'take part'? Quantitative data show that large numbers of people don't engage with formal cultural activities yet relatively little is known about these so-called 'non-users'.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>At issue here is a 'deficit' model of participation, which underpins policy narratives around increasing participation. In this view, cultural non-users are seen as a passive, isolated group needing to be engaged, both for personal benefit and the greater good of civic society.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This&amp;nbsp;research critiques this model by not presupposing the content of 'positive' participation and exploring the significance of mundane, neglected and opaque activities. Unpicking 'indicator' measures of participation it places engagement in a wider, relational perspective to probe the informal, everyday life processes which generate cultural and social (in)activity.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This&amp;nbsp;approach draws on two collections of qualitative in-depth interviews: one generated from an extensive sub-sample of the 1958 Birth Cohort Study; the other from a study of (dis)engagement with cultural institutions in Manchester. It is additionally framed by a profiling analysis of 'non-users' from the Taking Part survey.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This work is relevant to DCMS concerns with conceptualising engagement; understanding the contexts, motivations and outcomes of participation; targeting disadvantaged groups; and widening the evidence base for cultural policy. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-11-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>17541</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>61585220-D414-4805-B1ED-72D4573CDA3A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding participation in culture and sport: Mixing methods, reordering knowledges</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Cultural Trends</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/c52b1deea6d33589dd0d7adec320dbc6"><gtr:id>c52b1deea6d33589dd0d7adec320dbc6</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Miles A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>5463ac6fca2851.63433734</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2C57EEA6-F46D-4C41-BFF7-85D4394454F8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding the relationship between taste and value in culture and sport</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/01b4bb59faddcf309a6b101f15f303a3"><gtr:id>01b4bb59faddcf309a6b101f15f303a3</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Miles A G</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></g